'25:1': [
{sup:"1a", word:"fornication", vrefs:"Num. 31:16; 1&nbsp;Cor. 10:8; Rev. 2:14", lines:["Unable to defeat Israel militarily, politically, or through the use of religion, Balak, under the evil counsel of Balaam ({Num31:16|31:16}; {Rev2:14|Rev. 2:14}), induced Israel to fall into fornication and idolatry (vv. {Num25:1|1}-{Num25:3|3a}). Fornication destroys the person of the God-created man, and idolatry insults the divine person of God. According to the record of the Bible, fornication and idolatry go together ({Act15:29|Acts 15:29}; {1Co10:7|1&nbsp;Cor. 10:7}-{1Co10:8|8}; {Eph5:5|Eph. 5:5}).","God&rsquo;s view of Israel, revealed in Balaam&rsquo;s parables (chs. {Num23|23}&mdash;{Num24|24}), is altogether positive; but according to their actual situation and condition in their adamic nature, the children of Israel were fallen and sinful, a people of fornication and idolatry. The situation is the same with the believers in Christ. On the one hand, in Christ we are a heavenly people ({Eph2:6|Eph. 2:6}; {Phi3:20|Phil. 3:20a}; {Col3:1|Col. 3:1}-{Col3:3|3}); on the other hand, in ourselves we are a fallen and sinful people, worthy to be judged by God ({Rom7:18|Rom. 7:18}; {Eph2:1|Eph. 2:1}-{Eph2:3|3})."]},
],
