'36:6': [
{sup:1, word:"married", lines:["God allowed the daughters to marry according to their taste but only within the family of the tribe of their father. This indicates that although the Lord gives us freedom, this freedom must be exercised within the limit, the boundary, of God&rsquo;s regulation (cf. {Gal5:13|Gal. 5:13})."]},
],
'36:7': [
{sup:"a", word:"So", vrefs:"Num. 36:9"},
{sup:1, word:"cling", lines:["This signifies that as our inheritance Christ is not transferable and that we should cling to Him as this inheritance. In principle, for a believer to marry an unbeliever is to make Christ as the inheritance transferable (cf. {2Co6:14|2&nbsp;Cor. 6:14}). Cf. {Num27:7^1|note 7<sup>1</sup>} in {Num27|ch. 27}."]},
],
'36:8': [
{sup:"a", word:"daughter", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Chron. 23:22"},
{sup:1, word:"marry", lines:["The marriage of Mary, the mother of the Lord Jesus, to Joseph may be a marriage that fulfilled this statute (see {Mat1:16^1|note 16<sup>1</sup>} in {Mat1|Matt. 1}). Thus, the statute in this chapter was actually ordained by God for Christ&rsquo;s incarnation. All Scripture reveals Christ and is a record concerning Christ, either directly or indirectly ({Luk24:27|Luke 24:27}, {Luk24:44|44}). The cities of refuge in {Num35|ch. 35} are a type of Christ, and the settlement of the problem regarding the inheritance in {Num36|ch. 36} is related to Christ. If Christ had not been incarnated, He could not have become the cities of refuge for the human race. Thus, in a very real sense, the refuge cities in {Num35|ch. 35} depend on the statute in {Num36|ch. 36}."]},
],
